\begin_layout Standard
This chapter serves to summarize the methods and results shown in this thesis.
 The Tokai to Kamioka (T2K) experiment is a long baseline, neutrino oscillation
 experiment designed to observe a 
\begin_inset Formula $\numu$
\end_inset

 beam oscillate into 
\begin_inset Formula $\nue$
\end_inset

.
 With the aid of the Japan Proton Accelerator Research Complex (J-PARC),
 a dedicated near detector called ND280 is located downstream of the neutrino
 production source to observe the beam before oscillations occur.
 Since the start of data collection, the fine grain detector (FGD) in ND280
 has provided constraints on the neutrino flux and neutrino-water interaction
 modes important to the oscillation analysis.
 This thesis is an analysis of an independent measurement of the ND280 constrain
t using a maximum likelihood estimate in the Beam and Near Detector Flux
 Task Force (BANFF) framework with samples from the pi-zero detector (
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analysis samples have been developed with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

 to capture a wide variety of interaction modes in T2K, importantly interactions
 classified as charged current quasi-elastic (CCQE) which constitute the
 highest cross section in the T2K neutrino energy spectrum.
 While the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

 has a larger volume compared to the FGD, which means it has more neutrino
 interactions to select, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

 is less sensitive to non-CCQE interactions like CC single pion production.
 This limitation is largely due to the design of the detector and sample
 selection which reduce its 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(p,\cos\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 sensitivity to the lower energy outgoing muons.
 The systematic uncertainties inherent in the samples were controlled for
 in a similar manner with previous BANFF analyses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

-only data fit shows very good agreement with the FGD-only result using
 the same flux and cross section parameters.
 Trends in the postfit parameters like the flux shape and the quantum mechanical
 correlation affects on the observable cross section were observed in both
 sets of fits.
 A hypothesis test was conducted to test if the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

-only and FGD-only data fits are consistent with one another.
 The test produced
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\chi}^{2}=\frac{\chi^{2}}{\text{NDOF}}=\frac{81.41}{75},\quad p=0.2865,
\]

\end_inset

which indicates the test failed to reject the null hypothesis.
 
\shape italic
This is another way of saying the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pod$
\end_inset

 provides a similar ND280 constraint compared to the FGD
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Prediction of the T2K Oscillation Analysis Samples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we analyze the BANFF fit as the input for the oscillation
 analysis.
 We are explicitly NOT performing the oscillation analysis, but we are building
 a prediction of the oscillated neutrino samples using the frequentist framework
 described in the 2017 oscillation analysis publication
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Abe:2017vif"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We then compare the prediction with the observed neutrino energy spectra
 of the four CCQE-enriched samples at Super-Kamiokande (SK).
 These samples are the FHC mode (
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-mode) 
\begin_inset Formula $\numu$
\end_inset

 sample, the RHC mode (
\begin_inset Formula $\antinu$
\end_inset

-mode) 
\begin_inset Formula $\numubar$
\end_inset

 sample, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

-mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\nue$
\end_inset

 sample, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\antinu$
\end_inset

-mode 
\begin_inset Formula $\nuebar$
\end_inset

 sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The SK prediction is built with the following ingredients: the flux and
 cross section parameter estimates from the BANFF fit parameter estimates
 and covariance matrix, the nominal set of SK detector systematics in the
 frequentist analysis software, and the full three-flavor oscillation probabilit
ies.
 The full three-flavor oscillation parameters used are the same as listed
 in TABLE II in the 2018 CP violation search paper
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Abe:2018wpn"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, which are shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:Oscillation-parameters-used"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for convenience.
 The observed spectra are also taken from the 2018 CP violation search paper,
 which had a integrated luminosity of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.2\times10^{21}$
\end_inset

 POT.
\end_layout

