\begin_layout Subsection
Regularization Strength
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the BANFF ND constraint test statistic is defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\chi_{\text{ND280}}^{2} & =\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}\left(\vec{N}^{d},\vec{N}^{p}\right)+\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2}\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{N}^{d}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{N}^{p}$
\end_inset

 are the binned data and prediction measurements, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 is the difference between postfit and prefit parameter values in the fit.
 This equation is similar to the general class of parameter regression using
 regularization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "springer_series978-0-387-84858-7"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\hat{\beta} & =\underset{f\in\mathcal{F},\beta\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ L\left(\eta,f\left(\vec{\beta}\right)\right)+\lambda J\left(f\right)\right\} \end{aligned}
,\label{eq:GeneralRegularization}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a loss function
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is also called an objective function.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $J\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is a penalty function, 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(\vec{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the regularization parameter, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is a space of function on which 
\begin_inset Formula $J\left(f\right)$
\end_inset

 is defined.
 In regularized regression problems, the penalty term serves to solve an
 ill posed problem by adding external information.
 Similarly, the regularization parameter controls the importance of the
 penalty.
 We recognize that the loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the log-likelihood ratio term 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and penalty term is 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with regularization strength 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In defining the BANFF test statistic in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "chap:BANFF-Likelihood"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the regularization term 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 was set to 1 without justification.
 We can test the effectiveness of this choice using cross-validation.
 Cross-Validation provides an estimate on the prediction error as well as
 determines the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 choice of regularization.
 In cross-validation, the input data is randomly split into 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 equal sized partitions.
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in K$
\end_inset

 data partition, we fit the model to the other 
\begin_inset Formula $K-1$
\end_inset

 parts of the data and calculate a prediction error 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this verification of the regularization strength, the test statistic
 is altered to include a regularization term
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\chi_{\text{ND280}}^{2} & =\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}+\lambda\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2}\left(\vec{y}\right)\\
 & =\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}+\lambda\left(\vec{y}-\vec{y}_{0}\right)^{T}V^{-1}\left(\vec{y}-\vec{y}_{0}\right),
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:RegularizedDeltaChi2ND280}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the data is split into 
\begin_inset Formula $K=5$
\end_inset

 partitions.
 The prediction error, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, in this analysis is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{k}\left(\left(\chi_{\text{train}}^{2}\right)^{-k},\left(\chi_{\text{test}}^{2}\right)^{k}\right)=\left|\left(\chi_{\text{train}}^{2}\right)^{-k}-\left(\chi_{\text{test}}^{2}\right)^{k}\right|\label{eq:predictionerror}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\chi_{\text{train}}^{2}\right)^{-k}$
\end_inset

 is the fitted model statistic on all but the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th partition, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\chi_{\text{test}}^{2}\right)^{k}$
\end_inset

 is prediction from the fitted model on the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

th partition.
 This definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is useful since the penalty terms cancel, leaving only the difference in
 log-likelihood terms.
 The optimal regularization strength is determined by minimizing the cross-valid
ation error, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\text{CV}\left(\lambda\right) & =\left\langle \left|\chi_{\text{train}}^{2}-\chi_{\text{test}}^{2}\right|\right\rangle \\
 & =\frac{1}{5}\sum_{k=1}^{5}P_{k}\left(\left(\chi_{\text{train}}^{2}\right)^{-k},\left(\chi_{\text{test}}^{2}\right)^{k}\right),
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:CVerror}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is the average prediction error.
\end_layout

