\begin_layout Subsection
Alternative Penalty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider solving the linear regression problem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{\eta}=X\vec{\beta}\label{eq:LinearProblem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p\times d$
\end_inset

 matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 model features from 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 measurements, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\beta}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of regression weights with 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 rows, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is a response vector.
 There are many approaches to solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearProblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:GeneralRegularization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 A popular solution is the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

-regularization constraint
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "springer_series978-0-387-84858-7"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\vec{\beta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ L\left(\vec{\eta},\vec{\beta}\right)+\lambda\sum_{i}\left|\beta_{i}\right|^{2}\right\} \label{eq:RidgeRegressionGeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the sum of squares of the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{i}$
\end_inset

 sets the constraint and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is the loss function.
 A popular choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is using ordinary least squares 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L\left(\vec{\eta},\vec{\beta}\right)=\sum_{j}\left|\vec{\eta}-X\vec{\beta}\right|^{2},
\]

\end_inset

which provides the lowest variance in parameter weights.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With some algebra, we can rewrite the BANFF test statistic 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:minBANFFDeltaChiSqr"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the form of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionGeneral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 We again recognize 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 which leaves the penalty term to be tackled.
 The (inverse) covariance matrix is symmetric and real and can be decomposed
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V^{-1}=U^{T}\Lambda U
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 are the matrix of the eigenvectors and eigenvalues, respectively, of 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the eigenvalues are real and positive, the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as the square of a diagonal matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda=\Gamma^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

We can now rewrite the penalty term as an inner product of two vectors.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2} & =\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)^{T}V^{-1}\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\\
 & \left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)^{T}U^{T}\Gamma^{2}U\left(\Delta\vec{y}\right)\\
 & =\left(\Gamma U\Delta\vec{y}\right)^{T}\left(\Gamma U\Delta\vec{y}\right).
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\psi}=\Gamma U\Delta\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, then the penalty term becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\chi_{\text{Penalty}}^{2} & =\left(\vec{\psi}\right)^{T}\vec{\psi}=\sum_{j}\left|\psi_{j}\right|^{2}\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

and test statistic is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\chi_{\text{ND280}}^{2} & =\chi_{\text{LLR}}^{2}\left(N^{d},N^{p}\right)+\left|\left|\psi\right|\right|_{2}^{2}\end{aligned}
,\label{eq:DeltaChiSqND280RidgeRegressionForm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left|\ \right|\right|_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is shorthand for the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

-regularization constraint sum of squares.
 We see that the BANFF test statistic is indeed a 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

-regularized solution with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\vec{y}$
\end_inset

, recast as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\psi}$
\end_inset

, acting as the parameter weight vector and has the regularization strength
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider now another solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LinearProblem"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 using the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

-regularization constraint or least absolute shrinkage and selection operator
 (Lasso)
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Lasso or 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

-regularization constraint is commonly employed in parameter estimation
 problems in linear systems.
 For example, the method has been used in cancer class prediction with gene
 expression profiling in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

PAM
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 package
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ISI:000175637300012"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Lasso has also been shown to work with generalized linear models
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JSSv033i01"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{\vec{\beta}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}}{\text{argmin}}\left\{ L\left(\vec{\eta},\vec{\beta}\right)+\lambda\left|\left|\beta\right|\right|_{1}\right\} ,\label{eq:LassoRegressionGeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left|\ \right|\right|_{1}$
\end_inset

 indicates the sum of absolute values of the parameter weight terms.
 What is unique about the Lasso is its ability to promote model solutions
 with few nonzero coefficient weights, sometimes called sparse solutions.
 In other words, predictor parameters with no model impact are excluded
 in the solution using the 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{1}$
\end_inset

-regularized constraint.
 Thus the Lasso has the advantage of providing an interpretable model in
 situations with very high parameter spaces.
 However, the Lasso does not handle highly correlated variables very well.
 This is overcome by combining the Lasso with 
\begin_inset Formula $l_{2}$
\end_inset

-regularization which is called the elastic net constraint
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
